abstract: In a surprise visit that started a two-day blitz of Western allies, the Ukrainian president implored Britain to provide planes he said would represent “wings of freedom.’’
snippet: In a surprise visit that started a two-day blitz of Western allies, the Ukrainian president implored Britain to provide planes he said would represent “wings of freedom.’’
lead_paragraph: LONDON — President Volodymyr Zelensky of Ukraine pleaded with Britain on Wednesday to supply his country with fighter jets, making his dramatic appeal during a surprise visit to London that began a two-day diplomatic blitz of Ukraine’s Western allies.

main: Zelensky Brings a Shopping List to Britain, With Fighter Planes at the Top
print_headline: In London, First Stop on a Tour of Allies, Zelensky Asks for Fighter Jets

abstract: Hundreds attended a televised service for the outspoken Russian nationalist, where many vowed that Russia would win the war in Ukraine.
snippet: Hundreds attended a televised service for the outspoken Russian nationalist, where many vowed that Russia would win the war in Ukraine.
lead_paragraph: Hundreds of people, including lawmakers, writers and cultural leaders, attended a televised memorial service on Tuesday in Moscow for Daria Dugina, a right-wing commentator who was killed in a car bombing over the weekend, with many calling for vengeance and vowing that Russia would win the war in Ukraine.

main: At a televised memorial for Daria Dugina, many call for vengeance.
print_headline: At Memorial In Moscow, Many Calls For Revenge

abstract: At Time Warner, executives saw AT&T as just a “big phone company from Texas.” At AT&T, they thought Hollywood would play by their rules. That combination led to strategic miscalculation unrivaled in recent corporate history.
snippet: At Time Warner, executives saw AT&T as just a “big phone company from Texas.” At AT&T, they thought Hollywood would play by their rules. That combination led to strategic miscalculation unrivaled in recent corporate history.
lead_paragraph: Soon after a sweeping courtroom victory in 2018 cleared the way for AT&T’s $100 billion takeover of Time Warner, John Stankey, AT&T’s chief operating officer and the newly anointed chief executive of Warner Media, summoned his top Warner Media executives to a meeting at the Time Warner Center off Columbus Circle.

main: Was This $100 Billion Deal the Worst Merger Ever?
print_headline: How a Media Megadeal Went So Bad So Fast

abstract: The additions to Ukraine’s arsenal, which include more tanks, drones and other weapons from Germany, may signal that Western officials believe Kyiv’s forces could reclaim significant swaths of territory.
snippet: The additions to Ukraine’s arsenal, which include more tanks, drones and other weapons from Germany, may signal that Western officials believe Kyiv’s forces could reclaim significant swaths of territory.
lead_paragraph: The new long-range missiles, attack drones and tanks and other armored vehicles that President Volodymyr Zelensky has secured from allies in recent days will fulfill many, but not all, of the demands for weapons that Ukraine said it needs for a counteroffensive against Russia.

main: With a new tranche of weapons, Ukraine has much of what it needs for a counteroffensive, analysts say.

abstract: The iPhone maker is making a bold bet that it can redefine the niche category of virtual reality with its $3,500 goggles.
snippet: The iPhone maker is making a bold bet that it can redefine the niche category of virtual reality with its $3,500 goggles.
lead_paragraph: It’s here (or it will be “early next year”): Apple unveiled its long-awaited entry into virtual reality, or what the tech giant calls “spatial computing,” in the form of the Apple Vision Pro, a $3,500 device that looks like exquisitely designed futuristic ski goggles.

main: Can Apple Take the Metaverse Mainstream?

original: By Andrew Ross Sorkin, Ravi Mattu, Bernhard Warner, Sarah Kessler, Michael J. de la Merced, Lauren Hirsch and Ephrat Livni

abstract: How readers are adjusting to the end of daylight saving time.
snippet: How readers are adjusting to the end of daylight saving time.
lead_paragraph: Tomorrow morning, in the tiniest hours, daylight saving time ends. We regain the hour we lost in the spring, “one final consolation, handed out like a party favor popped into a child’s loot bag to soften the blow of going home, now that the party’s over,” as Joan Gould wrote in The Times in 1981.

abstract: As a Time magazine bureau chief, he was pivotal in the publication of revelatory taped interviews with the ousted premier that had been smuggled out of the Soviet Union.
snippet: As a Time magazine bureau chief, he was pivotal in the publication of revelatory taped interviews with the ousted premier that had been smuggled out of the Soviet Union.
lead_paragraph: Jerrold Schecter, a journalist who in the late 1960s helped smuggle to the West the revelatory memoirs of the former Soviet premier Nikita Khrushchev, the first published account by a Soviet leader of goings-on inside the Kremlin, died on Feb. 6 at his home in Washington. He was 90.

main: Jerrold Schecter, Who Procured Khrushchev’s Memoirs, Dies at 90
print_headline: Jerrold Schecter, Journalist, 90; Brought Khrushchev’s Memoirs to Light
